<br>
>First, 2 million DGU does not equal 2 million people. They are "uses". Someone could have had a DGU more than once. So, the first part of your statement is false. It could be true, but based on what Dumai said, it's not.<br>
<br>
Let me rephrase : this guy claims there have been 2 million DGUs in one year. What I am trying to concisely convey is that if your total population is 240 millions, close to one percent of the population has had to defend themself from a threat once this year with a gun on -average-.<br>
<br>
In other words : if you use your gun in repsonse to a criminal threat (mugging, whatever...), this would equal to a crime rate around 1000 per 100 000 (to translate into the kind of rates we were quoting before and not even accounting for cases where the victim did not have a gun to defend themself). Even assuming half of those DGUs where not in defense of violent criminal agression, you are still left with a ridiculously high number. Get it now ? <br>
<br>
Does it surprise you the guy retracted his claims as flawed and issued a new number ? Could it be because he was accounting for police enforcers when they draw their weapon while pulling a car for speed violation for instance ? Of course, we have no idea because the article quoting the study carefully leaves this out while leading you to believe that there are millions of brave citizens defending their lives with a gun yearly in our crime infested cities.<br>
<br>
>Your comparison to the current prison population is also flawed.<br>
<br>
It's not an argument, just a quantified idea of the percentage of the "hard" criminal population in the US. As you pointed out, a lot of people are "under correctional supervision", but you can also point out that the majority of those inmates are in for drug related crimes, not necessarily violent crime... It's about just as valid as the other study on the deterrent effect of firearms on inmates. Guess i'll have to go into that also later since a funny argument can be made about that too.  <br>
<br>
In the meantime I suggest you chew at those criminality figures from the BBC...<br>
<br>
S.<br>
